JACQUELINE FULLER: So let's
talk a little bit more

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:32.980
about your hospital
and the work there.

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:37.980
So was there a moment as you
were even thinking about,

00:16:37.980 --> 00:16:39.990
even to get more specific,
in my home country,

00:16:39.990 --> 00:16:42.090
I'm going to do work
here-- where you were like,

00:16:42.090 --> 00:16:43.298
it's going to be health care.

00:16:43.298 --> 00:16:45.490
It's going to be this hospital.

00:16:45.490 --> 00:16:47.800
And the way that you've
set it up is also unique.

00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:50.410
You and I were talking
about that in Florida

00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:53.670
that you've figured
out that there

00:16:53.670 --> 00:16:56.800
are ways to get some revenue
streams, because you can get

00:16:56.800 --> 00:17:00.350
people who need the care to
stop flying out of the country

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:01.680
to do so?

00:17:01.680 --> 00:17:03.520
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:09.050
The whole idea was just
getting the hospital created.

00:17:09.050 --> 00:17:12.839
The thing that hit me the
most was my mother's death,

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:14.470
when my mother
passed away, which

00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:17.450
was a sudden death at her home.

00:17:17.450 --> 00:17:21.810
And I realized that there
was something very important

00:17:21.810 --> 00:17:25.619
that I could do in this
country and make a difference

00:17:25.619 --> 00:17:27.880
for generations to come.

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:31.566
And I went and established
this wonderful organization,

00:17:31.566 --> 00:17:34.720
and we went and
built a hospital,

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:36.870
which did cost a lot of money.

00:17:36.870 --> 00:17:41.695
But as the hospital opened in
2007, we all did celebrate.

00:17:41.695 --> 00:17:42.990
We were full of joy.

00:17:42.990 --> 00:17:44.990
We were very happy.

00:17:44.990 --> 00:17:47.842
But we were losing
money at the beginning.

00:17:47.842 --> 00:17:48.800
JACQUELINE FULLER: Mhm.

00:17:48.800 --> 00:17:52.610
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: We were
losing a lot of money.

00:17:52.610 --> 00:17:57.570
We were losing close
to $3.5 million a year.

00:17:57.570 --> 00:18:04.350
And it was very difficult for me
to play basketball in the NBA,

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:09.890
and every day, I would force--
nobody didn't force me.

00:18:09.890 --> 00:18:13.930
But spiritually, I was forced
to raise money every day

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:17.660
in every city that I went
to, either before the game

00:18:17.660 --> 00:18:22.160
or after the game, I have to
come out with at least $350,000

00:18:22.160 --> 00:18:25.725
every year, every month, so
I can send to [INAUDIBLE],

00:18:25.725 --> 00:18:28.060
make sure the hospital
would stay open.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:32.790
And I did very well
with the generosity,

00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:37.120
with the support of so
many people in America.

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:41.071
And I woke up one day.

00:18:41.071 --> 00:18:41.570
I said, no.

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:43.090
It has to stop.

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:45.540
We have to stop
bleeding like this.

00:18:45.540 --> 00:18:47.800
We have to change the metrics.

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:52.290
So I talked to few people,
a few of my advisors,

00:18:52.290 --> 00:18:55.460
including Dr. [INAUDIBLE],
and Dr. [INAUDIBLE],

00:18:55.460 --> 00:18:58.620
and some of those people
who advise me every day.

00:18:58.620 --> 00:19:01.760
They say, Dikembe, you're
going to burn yourself up.

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:03.140
You cannot go like this.

00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:07.310
We have to figure out how
the hospital can make money.

00:19:07.310 --> 00:19:12.200
Then we realized
that in the Congo,

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:16.080
most of the corporations,
telecom industry,

00:19:16.080 --> 00:19:19.970
and the mining industry, was
losing close to $49 million

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:25.210
a year by shipping all the
executive and the top employees

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:29.010
to South Africa for treatment,
and getting a private plane

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:32.730
to take somebody who's having
a headache or a stomach pain.

00:19:32.730 --> 00:19:37.700
And I said, but if I can
invest more than $18 million

00:19:37.700 --> 00:19:40.780
in high tech equipment
in the Congo,

00:19:40.780 --> 00:19:43.170
we can stop losing all
this money every year,

00:19:43.170 --> 00:19:45.670
and all those people can come.

00:19:45.670 --> 00:19:49.070
So we went, and we talked
to a couple mining companies

00:19:49.070 --> 00:19:51.600
like Freeport in
Phoenix, Arizona,

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:54.500
that invests more than
$6 billion in the Congo.

00:19:54.500 --> 00:19:58.970
And they went and helped us
get more high tech equipment.

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.230
And today, all of
those companies

00:20:01.230 --> 00:20:04.060
are not shipping all their
employees to South Africa

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:04.840
anymore.

00:20:04.840 --> 00:20:08.440
And they come to us,
and they pay $20 a month

00:20:08.440 --> 00:20:10.341
for each one of the employees.

00:20:10.341 --> 00:20:12.590
Whenever they get sick, or
whenever they need surgery,

00:20:12.590 --> 00:20:15.760
they just get money
from the pool.

00:20:15.760 --> 00:20:20.785
And now, we have enough
money to run the hospital,

00:20:20.785 --> 00:20:26.360
to buy the medicine to
keep the hospital running.

00:20:26.360 --> 00:20:30.820
It's been a dream come true.

00:20:30.820 --> 00:20:32.090
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:20:32.090 --> 00:20:33.680
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
I can smile today.

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:37.240
I'll tell you guys, I was not
smiling the first three years.

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:38.060
It was tough.

00:20:38.060 --> 00:20:44.760
But now, I can laugh, and
enjoy myself, and travel a lot.

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:48.190
JACQUELINE FULLER: And in terms
of the challenges that you've

00:20:48.190 --> 00:20:50.810
seen, you've talked
about how you came up

00:20:50.810 --> 00:20:52.270
with a business solution.

00:20:52.270 --> 00:20:55.850
And as someone who's in the
giving business at google.org,

00:20:55.850 --> 00:20:58.960
I can say, we love when
non-profits come up

00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:02.170
with ways that they can cross
subsidize or have revenue

00:21:02.170 --> 00:21:05.400
streams, because it makes
the operation so much more

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:06.370
sustainable.

00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:10.490
But would you say that there's
other, key lessons that you've

00:21:10.490 --> 00:21:15.870
learned as a philanthropist
that maybe the Google employees

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:19.210
in this room might want
to keep in mind as they're

00:21:19.210 --> 00:21:20.640
doing their giving?

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:22.284
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:21:22.284 --> 00:21:27.814
I think the great lesson that I
learned, I wish as I get older,

00:21:27.814 --> 00:21:30.170
maybe I can continue
to teach unto

00:21:30.170 --> 00:21:35.240
those who want to get themselves
in the philanthropic world.

00:21:35.240 --> 00:21:39.025
That's do not go and
start an organization

00:21:39.025 --> 00:21:41.830
that you don't know how long
you're going to keep it going.

00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:44.530
 

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:46.840
First, it's not just your money.

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:48.940
It's the time.

00:21:48.940 --> 00:21:50.530
Make sure the
responsibility that you

00:21:50.530 --> 00:21:53.450
have in your life,
wife, or your husband,

00:21:53.450 --> 00:21:57.900
and your children have
been taken care of,

00:21:57.900 --> 00:22:00.790
and make sure that are
you in your workplace.

00:22:00.790 --> 00:22:02.760
Because you got to
keep working in life.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:06.030
You can't just stop
working and then

00:22:06.030 --> 00:22:09.125
devote yourself for the rest
of your life to philanthropy.

00:22:09.125 --> 00:22:12.220
 

00:22:12.220 --> 00:22:17.740
You will do it, but you have
to have revenue that will

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:20.220
keep the organization going.

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:22.070
I sit on so many boards.

00:22:22.070 --> 00:22:24.570
We raise money on a daily basis.

00:22:24.570 --> 00:22:28.330
Even the Special Olympics, we
have to keep the event going,

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:31.570
or we have to take care
of those young people.

00:22:31.570 --> 00:22:34.210
So you have to find a way how
the money will keep going.

00:22:34.210 --> 00:22:36.760
And our hospital
is surviving today,

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:40.067
because of all the
metrics, and all the things

00:22:40.067 --> 00:22:43.910
that we observe to learn
and mistakes that we made.

00:22:43.910 --> 00:22:46.620
We made a lot of mistakes.

00:22:46.620 --> 00:22:50.190
Today, we are happy
that we are partners

00:22:50.190 --> 00:22:54.020
with so many organizations,
including Google,

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:57.890
that [INAUDIBLE] to support us
in all the social innovation

00:22:57.890 --> 00:23:00.290
we're doing, not
just by bringing

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:06.600
all the Special Olympic kids
from the Congo to Los Angeles.

00:23:06.600 --> 00:23:09.980
So Google, the company
you work for, they're

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:14.520
supporting all of those doctors
from SEE international who

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:19.190
are coming to operate to
more than 250-some people who

00:23:19.190 --> 00:23:22.820
are losing their sight in the
Congo, that maybe tomorrow,

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:24.620
they're not going
to be able to see.

00:23:24.620 --> 00:23:26.410
So there's a lot of
great organizations

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:29.520
in Los Angeles who are
playing with their team,

00:23:29.520 --> 00:23:34.625
with the equipment, everything,
Google.org is supporting

00:23:34.625 --> 00:23:37.480
the organization so they
can come and operate

00:23:37.480 --> 00:23:39.320
in the hospital for two weeks.

00:23:39.320 --> 00:23:42.230
So we're happy with
this, all those marriages

00:23:42.230 --> 00:23:44.020
that we are having
with all those

00:23:44.020 --> 00:23:46.405
good people who
believe in our vision,

00:23:46.405 --> 00:23:48.590
because you will not
do it by yourself.

00:23:48.590 --> 00:23:49.939
That was my mistake.

00:23:49.939 --> 00:23:52.230
At the beginning, when I
started building the hospital.

00:23:52.230 --> 00:23:55.190
I was like, my name
is Dikembe Mutombo.

00:23:55.190 --> 00:23:59.220
I'm a millionaire, so I'm
just going to cut a check

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:00.320
and build a hospital.

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:01.850
That's it.

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:05.020
And the reason I
got to that point,

00:24:05.020 --> 00:24:09.930
because I got sick and tired
asking ball players for money.

00:24:09.930 --> 00:24:13.080
And I went to so
many of my friends.

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:15.380
As I will trying to approach
them to give me money,

00:24:15.380 --> 00:24:17.195
everybody was like--

00:24:17.195 --> 00:24:19.320
JACQUELINE FULLER: They
started to see you coming--

00:24:19.320 --> 00:24:21.861
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: And as soon as
they see me, as tall as I am,

00:24:21.861 --> 00:24:24.080
they just go to a
different direction.

00:24:24.080 --> 00:24:26.620
Deke, I'm not giving
him any money.

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:30.930
So it took them almost about
20 years before some of them

00:24:30.930 --> 00:24:33.570
decided even to give me $5,000.

00:24:33.570 --> 00:24:36.497
But that's a different story,
another day, we can talk about.

00:24:36.497 --> 00:24:39.080
JACQUELINE FULLER: We're going
to tell that story [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:39.080 --> 00:24:41.230
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
But I'm very happy.

00:24:41.230 --> 00:24:43.660
For me, any one of
you, anything you

00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:46.300
want to do, even
in your community,

00:24:46.300 --> 00:24:52.410
make sure that you put a great
team, that whatever you create,

00:24:52.410 --> 00:24:54.570
that you will work
with other partners.

00:24:54.570 --> 00:24:57.640
Don't try to do nothing
that you believe you're

00:24:57.640 --> 00:24:59.624
going to do it by yourself.

00:24:59.624 --> 00:25:03.060
I have so many
organizations supporting me,

00:25:03.060 --> 00:25:06.550
and that's the reason why the
hospital is running the way.

00:25:06.550 --> 00:25:11.860
It's tough to run the hospital
with 420 doctors and nurses,

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:14.320
and living in America,
not being there,

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:16.000
hoping that one day
when you come back,

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.210
all of the equipment's
going to be there.

00:25:18.210 --> 00:25:19.557
It's very tough.

00:25:19.557 --> 00:25:20.890
JACQUELINE FULLER: Good lessons.

00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:23.950
So let's shift gears a little
bit and talk about your role

00:25:23.950 --> 00:25:25.490
with sports diplomacy.

00:25:25.490 --> 00:25:28.280
So you've just gotten
back from a visit to Cuba

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:30.430
in your role as the
NBA's global ambassador.

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:31.680
So tell us about that.

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:33.750
What was Cuba like?

00:25:33.750 --> 00:25:35.491
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: It's beautiful.

00:25:35.491 --> 00:25:37.280
I'll tell you what.

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:41.242
I think it's maybe one of my
most beautiful experiences

00:25:41.242 --> 00:25:43.360
in the last decade.

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:45.140
I've had so many
great experiences

00:25:45.140 --> 00:25:48.626
before meeting Nelson
Mandela and all of that,

00:25:48.626 --> 00:25:50.000
when he came out
from the prison.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:56.510
But going to Cuba, who would
have ever thought that NBA,

00:25:56.510 --> 00:26:00.540
and we, as a basketball
player, we could go to Cuba

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:04.600
and host a basketball
clinic, and help

00:26:04.600 --> 00:26:07.972
those future generations
of young Cubans

00:26:07.972 --> 00:26:09.720
to have a bright future?

00:26:09.720 --> 00:26:11.460
JACQUELINE FULLER: Right.

00:26:11.460 --> 00:26:12.876
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
This is a country

00:26:12.876 --> 00:26:15.700
that is located almost 27
minutes away from the United

00:26:15.700 --> 00:26:17.580
States of America's shore.

00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:20.200
And it's just hopeful.

00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:22.920
For us, we, as
Americans, to just

00:26:22.920 --> 00:26:27.260
let other human beings
dye and suffer because

00:26:27.260 --> 00:26:29.050
of our political beliefs.

00:26:29.050 --> 00:26:33.735
And I'm glad that our
commissioner and our owners

00:26:33.735 --> 00:26:36.000
made that particular
decision that

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:42.190
said that we are going to Cuba
as part of the cultural change

00:26:42.190 --> 00:26:47.060
and building a bridge between
the Cubans and the Americans.

00:26:47.060 --> 00:26:50.380
And it was nothing to
do with the government.

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:54.110
It was all about human beings,
how can we, as humans, connect

00:26:54.110 --> 00:26:55.590
to each other with that.

00:26:55.590 --> 00:26:57.160
And we had a great time.

00:26:57.160 --> 00:26:59.400
We went there for seven days.

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:01.920
We did a lot of clinic.

00:27:01.920 --> 00:27:06.150
We refurbished more than
six basketball courts.

00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:09.210
We saw so many kids.

00:27:09.210 --> 00:27:11.440
To see kids in a
national team who

00:27:11.440 --> 00:27:13.860
come to practice every day
with no basketball shoes

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:15.162
that costs only $20--

00:27:15.162 --> 00:27:16.120
JACQUELINE FULLER: Wow.

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:18.710
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
It was very sad.

00:27:18.710 --> 00:27:22.020
We brought two
containers of shoes,

00:27:22.020 --> 00:27:24.420
and we gave it to every kid.

00:27:24.420 --> 00:27:27.130
You can see the
smiles on their face.

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:29.190
You see kids dribbling the ball.

00:27:29.190 --> 00:27:32.790
Instead of looking at the ball,
he's just looking at his feet.

00:27:32.790 --> 00:27:35.870
Oh my god, I've got
basketball shoes on.

00:27:35.870 --> 00:27:39.130
And that's what you want to see.

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:42.040
You want to see that
joy, and that happiness.

00:27:42.040 --> 00:27:44.280
We didn't meet with the
government officials.

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:46.220
They kind of left us alone.

00:27:46.220 --> 00:27:51.550
But it's something
that anyone of you

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:53.550
should go and take
that experience.

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:54.780
Cuba is not far.

00:27:54.780 --> 00:27:55.840
It's about six flights.

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:58.360
They went out from
the US to Cuba.

00:27:58.360 --> 00:28:01.840
So feel free, whenever
you have time, maybe

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:04.142
a weekend, just go to Cuba.

00:28:04.142 --> 00:28:06.350
JACQUELINE FULLER: Maybe
bring some basketball shoes.

00:28:06.350 --> 00:28:08.380
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
No, I'm serious.

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:11.740
You can travel to Cuba
now with no restrictions,

00:28:11.740 --> 00:28:13.880
for some of you that don't know.

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:16.770
Our embassy's opening.

00:28:16.770 --> 00:28:18.650
Maybe eight weeks
from now, we're

00:28:18.650 --> 00:28:21.280
going to have the embassy open.

00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:23.930
I believe John Kerry, if
he didn't break his legs,

00:28:23.930 --> 00:28:26.914
he was going to go
there very soon.

00:28:26.914 --> 00:28:29.330
JACQUELINE FULLER: That was
biking, not basketball though,

00:28:29.330 --> 00:28:29.710
right?

00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:30.445
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: That
was not basketball.

00:28:30.445 --> 00:28:32.950
JACQUELINE FULLER:
No, that was biking.

00:28:32.950 --> 00:28:35.510
So let me go back to something
you said a little bit earlier,

00:28:35.510 --> 00:28:38.110
which is that it took a
while for you to even talk

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:41.110
to some of your friends
in the NBA about giving.

00:28:41.110 --> 00:28:44.920
And there's this debate
about whether athletes

00:28:44.920 --> 00:28:47.930
are role models or
should be role models.

00:28:47.930 --> 00:28:50.595
I think you probably have
a perspective on that.

00:28:50.595 --> 00:28:51.470
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:28:51.470 --> 00:28:55.820
I believe that we,
as athletes, should

00:28:55.820 --> 00:28:57.950
be a role model in society.

00:28:57.950 --> 00:29:01.400
There's a lot of things
that we are responsible for.

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:04.380
We are the icon for the
next generation to come,

00:29:04.380 --> 00:29:08.800
and that we have maybe
a billion people who

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:10.380
follow us on a weekly basis.

00:29:10.380 --> 00:29:11.380
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:29:11.380 --> 00:29:13.630
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Especially
we, as basketball players.

00:29:13.630 --> 00:29:15.730
I think for the fact
that we wear a uniform.

00:29:15.730 --> 00:29:20.990
We don't wear
anything in our hair

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:22.800
to cover us like
football players.

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:26.160
But people know us by our faces.

00:29:26.160 --> 00:29:29.085
I think we should
be a role model.

00:29:29.085 --> 00:29:30.960
There's a lot of things
that we can stand on,

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:35.151
that we can do and make a
difference in our society.

00:29:35.151 --> 00:29:40.090
And I reject those
who come out publicly.

00:29:40.090 --> 00:29:42.980
I'm not against Charles
Barkley, and I love him so much.

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:44.770
He's a great guy.

00:29:44.770 --> 00:29:48.590
But I reject the idea that the
people who come publicly on TV

00:29:48.590 --> 00:29:51.220
say that I cannot
be a role model,

00:29:51.220 --> 00:29:56.330
or nobody is more about me,
because if it's all about you,

00:29:56.330 --> 00:29:58.259
how did you get there?

00:29:58.259 --> 00:29:59.300
JACQUELINE FULLER: Right.

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:02.430
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: How did you get
to be a great NBA player if you

00:30:02.430 --> 00:30:06.220
didn't get support from
your coaches, your teammate,

00:30:06.220 --> 00:30:09.790
your friends, and your high
school teacher, your principle,

00:30:09.790 --> 00:30:11.340
or your mom and dad.

00:30:11.340 --> 00:30:13.445
You did have so many
people who did believe

00:30:13.445 --> 00:30:17.195
in you, who did believe
in your vision, who said,

00:30:17.195 --> 00:30:19.480
I will put my trust in this kid.

00:30:19.480 --> 00:30:21.630
I'm going to put my
effort in this child,

00:30:21.630 --> 00:30:25.280
and I'm going to try to help
him to get to the [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:28.180
to go, because they want
to make you an example.

00:30:28.180 --> 00:30:33.230
So there's a responsibility
in each one of us to do.

00:30:33.230 --> 00:30:38.860
As one of the professors put
it in a summit in an AIDS

00:30:38.860 --> 00:30:40.880
conference in South Africa.

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:43.520
He said that when there's
a problem affecting

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:44.850
one part of the society.

00:30:44.850 --> 00:30:48.010
It should be a responsibility
of a human being living

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:49.020
on this planet.

00:30:49.020 --> 00:30:51.800
Somehow, every human being
living on this planet,

00:30:51.800 --> 00:30:53.270
somehow, we have a role to do.

00:30:53.270 --> 00:30:57.350
We have a duty to fulfill
for other human beings.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.290
It doesn't matter which
part of the world,

00:30:59.290 --> 00:31:02.510
which part of society that
you live in or you work in.

00:31:02.510 --> 00:31:08.230
There's always a place for you
to contribute to be an example.

00:31:08.230 --> 00:31:11.380
So these are the great
examples that I'm

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:12.870
giving to each one of you.

00:31:12.870 --> 00:31:14.560
Don't say that
because I work here

00:31:14.560 --> 00:31:16.940
in this beautiful,
magnificent campus,

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:19.990
I don't have any role
outside of this campus.

00:31:19.990 --> 00:31:21.610
You do.

00:31:21.610 --> 00:31:25.170
You're a role model too,
not just Dikembe Mutombo.

00:31:25.170 --> 00:31:26.370
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:26.370 --> 00:31:29.030
JACQUELINE FULLER: Uh-huh.

00:31:29.030 --> 00:31:31.390
So are there any
players or people

00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:34.490
that you would call out as
people who are doing it well?

00:31:34.490 --> 00:31:35.365
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:31:35.365 --> 00:31:38.300
 

00:31:38.300 --> 00:31:43.330
The best of them,
I will say today,

00:31:43.330 --> 00:31:48.480
who's really following
almost 99.9% in my footsteps,

00:31:48.480 --> 00:31:50.030
I would say, Yao Ming.

00:31:50.030 --> 00:31:51.040
JACQUELINE FULLER: Oh.

00:31:51.040 --> 00:31:53.170
Yeah, from China.

00:31:53.170 --> 00:31:55.410
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: To see
how much in resources

00:31:55.410 --> 00:32:00.870
that the young man has devoted
himself to more than 1.2

00:32:00.870 --> 00:32:02.690
billion people in China.

00:32:02.690 --> 00:32:05.410
He's building schools.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:10.070
He's building a bunch
of sports academies.

00:32:10.070 --> 00:32:14.370
He's building recreation centers
for after school programs.

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:17.117
I thought I was doing enough.

00:32:17.117 --> 00:32:18.950
JACQUELINE FULLER: Is
he raising the stakes?

00:32:18.950 --> 00:32:20.610
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: As
being tall as I am.

00:32:20.610 --> 00:32:25.630
But seeing other guys
who's taller than me,

00:32:25.630 --> 00:32:29.207
almost at 7'7",
that I can look up.

00:32:29.207 --> 00:32:30.165
JACQUELINE FULLER: Wow.

00:32:30.165 --> 00:32:31.800
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: And I say, no.

00:32:31.800 --> 00:32:33.080
That's my role model.

00:32:33.080 --> 00:32:34.290
JACQUELINE FULLER: Wow.

00:32:34.290 --> 00:32:36.895
Another man that Dikembe
actually has to look up to.

00:32:36.895 --> 00:32:37.770
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:38.920
Oh, there's a few of them.

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:39.920
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:41.770
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: I'm
not the tallest guy.

00:32:41.770 --> 00:32:46.480
I'm a little bit tall, but
I see tall people every day.

00:32:46.480 --> 00:32:49.160
But I'm very glad
that [INAUDIBLE] you

00:32:49.160 --> 00:32:53.040
have Luol Deng, who's
playing for the Miami Heat.

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:55.400
He's doing so much
in Southern Sudan.

00:32:55.400 --> 00:32:56.960
You have Alonzo Mourning.

00:32:56.960 --> 00:32:59.595
He's done so much in Miami.

00:32:59.595 --> 00:33:01.180
You have LeBron James.

00:33:01.180 --> 00:33:06.319
He's becoming very devoted
for the city of Akron,

00:33:06.319 --> 00:33:07.485
also, the city of Cleveland.

00:33:07.485 --> 00:33:10.000
 

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:11.540
We have so many, old and young.

00:33:11.540 --> 00:33:15.950
You have all the kids
who are coming out.

00:33:15.950 --> 00:33:21.410
You have Kevin Garnett,
and Serge Ibaka,

00:33:21.410 --> 00:33:25.020
and all those young kids who are
coming for the new generation

00:33:25.020 --> 00:33:26.900
are trying to keep
up with my footsteps.

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:30.210
And we're so happy that
so many of our players

00:33:30.210 --> 00:33:32.580
today are stepping up.

00:33:32.580 --> 00:33:36.480
They came to understand
that this game is good.

00:33:36.480 --> 00:33:38.160
We make money.

00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:42.140
But we have to make a difference
in our society, because I would

00:33:42.140 --> 00:33:45.900
not be sitting in this
chair that you put me in,

00:33:45.900 --> 00:33:48.450
not just because of
the game of basketball.

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:50.630
There's other things
that you appreciate

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:53.610
about me and my
personality, and that's

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:56.690
the reason why you guys brought
me in this beautiful campus.

00:33:56.690 --> 00:34:02.305
And I think we want our
place to be that model.

00:34:02.305 --> 00:34:05.090
 

00:34:05.090 --> 00:34:10.560
Just do what you can do, because
you cannot be here forever.

00:34:10.560 --> 00:34:14.856
JACQUELINE FULLER: So NBA
finals start tomorrow night.

00:34:14.856 --> 00:34:15.980
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: I'm going.

00:34:15.980 --> 00:34:20.394
 

00:34:20.394 --> 00:34:22.810
JACQUELINE FULLER: So I was
going to ask, who's your pick?

00:34:22.810 --> 00:34:24.159
And you have to be gentle.

00:34:24.159 --> 00:34:26.270
And remember, we've got
a lot of Warriors fans

00:34:26.270 --> 00:34:27.940
perhaps in this room.

00:34:27.940 --> 00:34:29.449
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: You know what?

00:34:29.449 --> 00:34:37.370
I apologize that I cannot
predict who's going to win Not

00:34:37.370 --> 00:34:39.190
just because I'm a
basketball player,

00:34:39.190 --> 00:34:42.140
but I work for the
commissioner office.

00:34:42.140 --> 00:34:43.829
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:43.829 --> 00:34:45.370
JACQUELINE FULLER:
As ambassador, one

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:46.376
does not pick teams.

