00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:55.467
And I'm going to take my fifth.

00:34:55.467 --> 00:34:58.640
But I wish you guys good luck.

00:34:58.640 --> 00:35:00.700
It's the best for my job.

00:35:00.700 --> 00:35:05.320
It makes me look good, and
it'll be good if your city wins,

00:35:05.320 --> 00:35:07.120
your team wins.

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:10.540
We're all going to be here to
celebrate, but I'm just happy.

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:11.970
It's the best for the game.

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:14.340
All these ideas are
good for the game.

00:35:14.340 --> 00:35:16.520
JACQUELINE FULLER: All right.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:20.680
So what does it feel like
to block Michael Jordan?

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:24.730
 

00:35:24.730 --> 00:35:26.480
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: I've
have a great respect

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:29.440
in the game of Michael Jordan.

00:35:29.440 --> 00:35:33.020
And I have a great respect for
Michael, himself, as a player,

00:35:33.020 --> 00:35:34.540
as a person.

00:35:34.540 --> 00:35:40.990
But he was one of those
guys that I always said,

00:35:40.990 --> 00:35:42.684
this guy's not going to get me.

00:35:42.684 --> 00:35:43.600
JACQUELINE FULLER: Ah.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:44.480
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
As Dikembe Mutombo.

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:45.790
JACQUELINE FULLER: A
little bit competitive?

00:35:45.790 --> 00:35:46.665
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:35:46.665 --> 00:35:48.980
 

00:35:48.980 --> 00:35:51.520
I think Michael's one
of those guys that

00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:54.350
made me to be Dikembe Mutombo.

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:56.400
I just challenged him every day.

00:35:56.400 --> 00:36:00.360
And it took him about
7.5 years to get one.

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:01.634
JACQUELINE FULLER: Wow.

00:36:01.634 --> 00:36:04.050
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: As many years
as he played in the league,

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:04.822
he only got one.

00:36:04.822 --> 00:36:05.780
JACQUELINE FULLER: Wow.

00:36:05.780 --> 00:36:07.363
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: And
I always told him

00:36:07.363 --> 00:36:10.940
that he got me
because I was late.

00:36:10.940 --> 00:36:13.710
He really didn't get me.

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:15.988
He really didn't
climb over my Mutombo.

00:36:15.988 --> 00:36:16.936
JACQUELINE FULLER: OK.

00:36:16.936 --> 00:36:19.306
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:19.306 --> 00:36:21.804
[APPLAUSE]

00:36:21.804 --> 00:36:23.220
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
You can ask him--

00:36:23.220 --> 00:36:24.320
JACQUELINE FULLER: I'll ask him.

00:36:24.320 --> 00:36:25.065
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: --friend.

00:36:25.065 --> 00:36:26.790
But see, I'm a
super Sonic friend,

00:36:26.790 --> 00:36:28.910
they know how they try
to climb over Mutombo.

00:36:28.910 --> 00:36:31.410
JACQUELINE FULLER: So we're not
going to the Sonics, are we?

00:36:31.410 --> 00:36:33.370
We are just not going
to go the Sonics.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.080
I think we have a live question.

00:36:35.080 --> 00:36:37.385
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
your vision for the Congo.

00:36:37.385 --> 00:36:39.510
And obviously, the hospital
is a huge part of that.

00:36:39.510 --> 00:36:41.230
But I'd love to hear
just more of what

00:36:41.230 --> 00:36:43.530
is your vision for the Congo.

00:36:43.530 --> 00:36:49.770
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: My vision is
I hope that Congo will become

00:36:49.770 --> 00:36:58.740
a country where people are
free to elect their leader,

00:36:58.740 --> 00:37:02.410
where everything
can be transparent,

00:37:02.410 --> 00:37:07.552
and where health care
and the mortality rate

00:37:07.552 --> 00:37:09.830
can go a little bit up.

00:37:09.830 --> 00:37:14.720
Right now, I still have my
brothers and sisters, uncles,

00:37:14.720 --> 00:37:17.020
cousins still living there.

00:37:17.020 --> 00:37:19.150
My mother-in-law's
still living there.

00:37:19.150 --> 00:37:26.190
So the mortality rate's still
42 for men and 43 for women.

00:37:26.190 --> 00:37:28.057
JACQUELINE FULLER: I'd be gone.

00:37:28.057 --> 00:37:29.640
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: I'm
working very hard

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:33.570
to see that mortality
rate maybe go to 50, 55.

00:37:33.570 --> 00:37:36.290
And I'm just putting
myself as an example.

00:37:36.290 --> 00:37:38.490
I'm not going to be just
the only one doing it.

00:37:38.490 --> 00:37:41.860
There's a lot of organizations
working in the Congo.

00:37:41.860 --> 00:37:44.280
We need to help
from the outside,

00:37:44.280 --> 00:37:46.340
not just for the
Congolese themselves.

00:37:46.340 --> 00:37:51.670
I think it will take the world
community to come together

00:37:51.670 --> 00:37:56.400
to figure out where's the best
way for Congo to move forward,

00:37:56.400 --> 00:38:03.050
because Congo's just a country
so rich with natural resources.

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:07.585
And everyone is digging in.

00:38:07.585 --> 00:38:10.820
It's not just the
Chinese who are there,

00:38:10.820 --> 00:38:14.870
but you also have the
Canadians, the Americans.

00:38:14.870 --> 00:38:18.700
So hopefully, all those
countries who feel like they

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:22.720
can benefit from the
Congolese natural resources.

00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:27.990
They can also invest
in the way human beings

00:38:27.990 --> 00:38:32.750
for Congolese people that
something is missing.

00:38:32.750 --> 00:38:34.950
The Canadian company,
the American company,

00:38:34.950 --> 00:38:37.840
the Chinese company, and
few European companies,

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:40.110
I think they benefit
for themselves.

00:38:40.110 --> 00:38:42.520
They're not putting
anything back

00:38:42.520 --> 00:38:45.945
so Congo can be a better
society and a better country.

00:38:45.945 --> 00:38:49.594
We will see how it goes
in the next five years.

