AUDIENCE: With Mobutu
Sese Seko gone, and I

00:40:55.220 --> 00:40:56.514
assume corruption's improving.

00:40:56.514 --> 00:40:57.930
But could you talk
about if you've

00:40:57.930 --> 00:40:59.346
had to navigate
through corruption

00:40:59.346 --> 00:41:02.360
through your
philanthropic efforts?

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:04.320
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
That's a good question.

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:07.230
I think corruption in
the African continent

00:41:07.230 --> 00:41:11.730
is never going to
erased, period.

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:16.110
Those are the things that all
the international communities

00:41:16.110 --> 00:41:19.340
need to know about.

00:41:19.340 --> 00:41:24.710
The reason I say that even
[INAUDIBLE] very good on that.

00:41:24.710 --> 00:41:27.800
I learn the corruption
from you guys,

00:41:27.800 --> 00:41:30.200
from the international
community.

00:41:30.200 --> 00:41:34.250
He said, you guys cannot come
and tell me that I'm corrupt,

00:41:34.250 --> 00:41:37.150
when it was you guys, one,
who came in my country,

00:41:37.150 --> 00:41:40.530
trying to get whatever we
have, and trying to pull him

00:41:40.530 --> 00:41:42.050
on the side, at the same time.

00:41:42.050 --> 00:41:46.500
And I think we see
corruption almost

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:52.510
in every part of society,
including here, in America.

00:41:52.510 --> 00:41:55.050
But the thing is when
the corruption reaches

00:41:55.050 --> 00:41:57.560
a different level,
and then that's

00:41:57.560 --> 00:42:00.060
when things doesn't look good.

00:42:00.060 --> 00:42:08.720
But the government
needs to work very hard.

00:42:08.720 --> 00:42:12.470
The country can be corrupt,
but at the same time,

00:42:12.470 --> 00:42:16.490
there can be other areas
where there's an advancement.

00:42:16.490 --> 00:42:20.240
And when we were
building our hospital,

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:23.040
I did face a lot of challenge.

00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:27.405
We had ministers, and
people in the government,

00:42:27.405 --> 00:42:30.412
in the lower level who
was coming and saying,

00:42:30.412 --> 00:42:31.870
you're not getting
these documents,

00:42:31.870 --> 00:42:33.790
or you're not getting
the permit for land

00:42:33.790 --> 00:42:39.240
or for the construction if
we don't see something back,

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:41.910
like a kick back.

00:42:41.910 --> 00:42:43.800
I'll give you an example.

00:42:43.800 --> 00:42:55.740
We had the groundbreaking of the
hospital on September 11, 2001.

00:42:55.740 --> 00:42:58.780
That was the day that the two
planes went through the World

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:01.190
Trade Center in New York.

00:43:01.190 --> 00:43:06.820
So the reason I always
say that my idea survived,

00:43:06.820 --> 00:43:10.170
comes from a very
difficult time,

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:13.450
because it was in the
middle of the ceremony

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:16.740
where the US ambassador,
with all of the diplomats

00:43:16.740 --> 00:43:19.810
who came with me on the
groundbreaking of the hospital,

00:43:19.810 --> 00:43:21.690
before the construction start.

00:43:21.690 --> 00:43:25.380
We have to stop the ceremony,
in the middle of the ceremony,

00:43:25.380 --> 00:43:29.180
because all of the US diplomats
and everybody from the US

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:32.920
government that was with me,
you have to leave the site,

00:43:32.920 --> 00:43:35.540
because there was
a terrorist attack.

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:40.630
So then I have to stop even my
construction for four years.

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:45.170
And I stopped the fundraising,
and the hospital was not

00:43:45.170 --> 00:43:47.635
going to get built. And we
didn't start the construction

00:43:47.635 --> 00:43:49.960
back until 2004.

00:43:49.960 --> 00:43:53.070
And then the hospital was
opened three years later.

00:43:53.070 --> 00:43:54.330
But it's a struggle.

00:43:54.330 --> 00:43:57.422
It's a struggle that
we went through.

00:43:57.422 --> 00:44:01.975
In 2004, I want to
see President Kabila.

00:44:01.975 --> 00:44:06.230
And I asked, Mr.
President, I said,

00:44:06.230 --> 00:44:08.660
I'm not starting
construction to the hospital

00:44:08.660 --> 00:44:11.450
until I get all the
documents that I want.

00:44:11.450 --> 00:44:14.005
He said, but Dikembe,
you made a promise

00:44:14.005 --> 00:44:16.675
to the Congolese people you
were going to build a hospital.

00:44:16.675 --> 00:44:19.400
It has been four
years that's went by.

00:44:19.400 --> 00:44:20.590
There's no break.

00:44:20.590 --> 00:44:22.000
Nothing's happening on the site.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:23.470
What happened?

00:44:23.470 --> 00:44:25.290
You have all of us
on the side there.

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:26.495
You make us look bad.

00:44:26.495 --> 00:44:29.180
I said, yeah, but
there's a couple people

00:44:29.180 --> 00:44:32.420
here in the lower level, who's
beating me up, or punching me

00:44:32.420 --> 00:44:33.045
every day.

00:44:33.045 --> 00:44:35.620
I need all the papers I can.

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:37.995
So one, we were
making sure that if we

00:44:37.995 --> 00:44:40.540
were going to bring
more than $18 million

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:44.460
of medical equipment
from Germany, and the US,

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:47.660
and other parts of the
world, we were making sure

00:44:47.660 --> 00:44:53.290
that those equipments, it was
in the Congo with no taxes,

00:44:53.290 --> 00:44:56.400
because I was investing millions
of dollars to the people

00:44:56.400 --> 00:44:59.810
and the future of the society,
why the same society would

00:44:59.810 --> 00:45:03.213
trying to tax me for
another $10 million?

00:45:03.213 --> 00:45:07.520
I said, I'm about to give
you guys a $20 million

00:45:07.520 --> 00:45:09.580
medical facility, and
you guys are trying

00:45:09.580 --> 00:45:11.030
to tax me $10 million more.

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:12.305
I said, let's do this.

00:45:12.305 --> 00:45:15.050
How about me just staying in
America, enjoying my money,

00:45:15.050 --> 00:45:17.920
and you guys stay over there,
while people are dying?

00:45:17.920 --> 00:45:20.697
So the government
ended up deciding, no.

00:45:20.697 --> 00:45:22.280
You're going to get
whatever you want,

00:45:22.280 --> 00:45:24.370
and I got everything I wanted.

00:45:24.370 --> 00:45:27.340
And I'll go to
the Congo everyday

00:45:27.340 --> 00:45:29.895
with nobody bothering me.

00:45:29.895 --> 00:45:31.270
JACQUELINE FULLER:
Well, I'm glad

00:45:31.270 --> 00:45:32.790
that you're sharing
the struggle,

00:45:32.790 --> 00:45:36.020
because I think sometimes,
we feel like when I give,

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:37.980
and when I want to
establish this nonprofit,

00:45:37.980 --> 00:45:40.320
and when I want to take on
affordable housing in the Bay

00:45:40.320 --> 00:45:41.695
Area, that should
be easy, right?

00:45:41.695 --> 00:45:43.850
You just mean well, and
you put in your resources,

00:45:43.850 --> 00:45:44.850
and things work out.

00:45:44.850 --> 00:45:49.237
So I think this tenacity
that you're talking about,

00:45:49.237 --> 00:45:51.820
and the fact that struggles are
going to come, and opposition,

00:45:51.820 --> 00:45:53.910
and then you have to
be creative, creative

00:45:53.910 --> 00:45:57.640
as a businessman,
creative as an operator

00:45:57.640 --> 00:46:00.760
to overcome that, I think that
that makes the story actually

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:02.010
even more inspiring, to hear--

00:46:02.010 --> 00:46:02.610
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO:
Sometimes, you've

00:46:02.610 --> 00:46:04.480
got to be a little bit mean.

00:46:04.480 --> 00:46:05.910
JACQUELINE FULLER: And
sometimes, a little bit mean.

00:46:05.910 --> 00:46:06.785
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:46:06.785 --> 00:46:10.800
When you're trying to
work, you will get people,

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:13.980
even from the city council,
from the government, who

00:46:13.980 --> 00:46:15.770
will try to come push
it, because you're

00:46:15.770 --> 00:46:20.090
making higher people who came
to me, even in Africa, who said,

00:46:20.090 --> 00:46:21.450
you know what?

00:46:21.450 --> 00:46:23.190
Thank you for
everything you're doing,

00:46:23.190 --> 00:46:25.845
but you do make us
embarrassed a little bit.

00:46:25.845 --> 00:46:28.230
You do embarrass
us, because you make

00:46:28.230 --> 00:46:32.780
us look bad, because we feel
like we're not doing anything.

00:46:32.780 --> 00:46:35.450
Every year, you always
bring all those people here,

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:37.080
doing all those surgeries.

00:46:37.080 --> 00:46:39.490
And then after you leave,
we don't do anything.

00:46:39.490 --> 00:46:40.821
People say, how about you?

00:46:40.821 --> 00:46:42.320
Why are you guys
not doing anything?

00:46:42.320 --> 00:46:44.910
So those are the challenges
you have to accept,

00:46:44.910 --> 00:46:47.430
and you have to
try to live with.

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:51.690
Do not try to have somebody
push you off the cliff,

00:46:51.690 --> 00:46:52.730
and you fall?

00:46:52.730 --> 00:46:54.271
JACQUELINE FULLER:
How would you like

00:46:54.271 --> 00:46:56.080
to be the person
trying to push him off?

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:56.789
This is the man--

00:46:56.789 --> 00:46:59.246
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: I've got a
lot of people trying to push me

00:46:59.246 --> 00:47:01.970
for the rebound, and I tried--
they got a lot of broken noses.

00:47:01.970 --> 00:47:02.597
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:47:02.597 --> 00:47:03.846
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Look at that.

00:47:03.846 --> 00:47:07.270
JACQUELINE FULLER: Apparently,
somebody-- it wasn't me--

00:47:07.270 --> 00:47:11.180
but somebody said maybe 22
broken noses on the other side

00:47:11.180 --> 00:47:12.040
of that elbow?

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:12.873
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: No.

00:47:12.873 --> 00:47:14.360
You know what?

00:47:14.360 --> 00:47:19.630
I always get accused for
being too aggressive.

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:22.590
And I think I really didn't
break anybody's nose.

00:47:22.590 --> 00:47:24.116
They ran up to my elbow.

00:47:24.116 --> 00:47:25.940
JACQUELINE FULLER: They ran.

00:47:25.940 --> 00:47:27.600
Some faces running into elbows.

00:47:27.600 --> 00:47:29.310
But what you're
saying is sometimes,

00:47:29.310 --> 00:47:30.850
even in the charitable
world, you've

00:47:30.850 --> 00:47:32.380
got to be a little aggressive.

00:47:32.380 --> 00:47:33.255
DIKEMBE MUTOMBO: Yes.

00:47:33.255 --> 00:47:34.600
You have to.

00:47:34.600 --> 00:47:37.450
Otherwise, they're going to beat
you up, and take your money,

00:47:37.450 --> 00:47:39.019
and run away.

00:47:39.019 --> 00:47:41.435
JACQUELINE FULLER: So you have
to practice Dikembe's style

00:47:41.435 --> 00:47:42.630
of philanthropy.

00:47:42.630 --> 00:47:43.130
I love that.

